¬(A ∧ B) ↔ (¬A ∨ ¬B)

(A → B) ↔ (¬B → ¬A)
(A → B) ↔ (¬A ∨ B)
(¬A → B) ↔ (A ∨ ¬B)

Which of the above is not logically equivalent to the rest? Provide the full statement that doesn't fit.
analysis: The user is asking to identify which logical equivalence is not valid among the given options. Each statement is a biconditional asserting equivalence between two expressions. Valid logical equivalences include De Morgan's Laws (1st and 2nd), contrapositive (3rd), implication-disjunction equivalence (4th and 6th), and the negation of implication (6th). The fifth statement, (¬A → B) ↔ (A ∨ ¬B), is invalid because ¬A → B converts to A ∨ B via material implication, which does not match A ∨ ¬B. This discrepancy makes it the only non-equivalent statement.
